# Project Rules for AdmissionTimes-backend

## Code Standards
- Follow SOLID principles (Single Responsibility, Open/Closed, Liskov Substitution, Interface Segregation, Dependency Inversion)
- Use design patterns where appropriate (Repository, Factory, Strategy, Observer, etc.)
- Write comprehensive comments for all code modules, functions, and complex logic
- Implement proper error handling and monitoring
- Use meaningful variable and function names (camelCase for variables/functions, PascalCase for classes)
- Avoid magic numbers and strings - use constants or configuration
- Keep functions small and focused (single responsibility)
- Prefer composition over inheritance
- Use async/await instead of callbacks or promises chains
- Always handle async errors with try-catch blocks

## Project Structure
- Keep code organized in modular structure
- Separate concerns (controllers, services, models, routes, middleware, utils)
- Use middleware for cross-cutting concerns (authentication, logging, validation, error handling)
- Maintain clear separation between business logic and API layer
- Controllers should only handle HTTP requests/responses, delegate business logic to services
- Services contain business logic and interact with models/repositories
- Models define data structures and database schemas
- Routes define API endpoints and map to controllers
- Utils contain reusable helper functions
- Config contains configuration files and environment setup

## API Design Best Practices
- Use RESTful conventions for endpoint naming (GET, POST, PUT, PATCH, DELETE)
- Use proper HTTP status codes (200, 201, 400, 401, 403, 404, 500, etc.)
- Implement consistent response format across all endpoints
- Use versioning for APIs (e.g., /api/v1/users)
- Implement pagination for list endpoints
- Use query parameters for filtering, sorting, and searching
- Return appropriate error messages without exposing sensitive information
- Implement rate limiting to prevent abuse
- Use proper HTTP methods (GET for retrieval, POST for creation, PUT for full updates, PATCH for partial updates, DELETE for deletion)
- Follow REST resource naming conventions (use nouns, not verbs)

## Security Best Practices
- Never commit sensitive data (passwords, API keys, tokens) to version control
- Use environment variables for all configuration and secrets
- Implement authentication and authorization for protected routes
- Use HTTPS in production
- Validate and sanitize all user inputs
- Implement CORS properly (restrict origins in production)
- Use parameterized queries to prevent SQL injection
- Implement password hashing (bcrypt, argon2) - never store plain text passwords
- Use JWT tokens with appropriate expiration times
- Implement refresh token mechanism
- Validate JWT tokens on protected routes
- Use helmet.js for security headers
- Implement input validation using libraries like Joi or express-validator
- Sanitize user inputs to prevent XSS attacks
- Implement CSRF protection where needed
- Use secure session management
- Never expose stack traces in production error responses

## Database Best Practices
- Use migrations for database schema changes
- Implement database connection pooling
- Use transactions for operations that must succeed or fail together
- Implement proper indexing for frequently queried fields
- Avoid N+1 query problems - use eager loading or batch queries
- Use database constraints (foreign keys, unique constraints, not null)
- Implement soft deletes where appropriate (isDeleted flag instead of hard delete)
- Use database-level validation in addition to application-level validation
- Implement database backups and recovery procedures
- Use connection retry logic for database connections
- Close database connections properly
- Use prepared statements/parameterized queries

## Validation & Data Handling
- Validate all input data at the API boundary (routes/middleware)
- Use validation libraries (Joi, express-validator, zod) for schema validation
- Validate data types, formats, ranges, and required fields
- Sanitize user inputs to prevent injection attacks
- Validate file uploads (type, size, content)
- Implement data transformation layers (DTOs - Data Transfer Objects)
- Never trust client-side validation alone - always validate on the server
- Return clear validation error messages

## Error Handling
- Use centralized error handling middleware
- Create custom error classes for different error types
- Provide clear, user-friendly error messages
- Log detailed error information for debugging (stack traces, context)
- Never expose sensitive information in error responses
- Use appropriate HTTP status codes for different error types
- Implement error recovery mechanisms where possible
- Handle async errors properly (use try-catch or error handlers)
- Implement global error handler as last middleware
- Return consistent error response format

## Logging Best Practices
- Use structured logging (JSON format recommended)
- Log at appropriate levels (error, warn, info, debug)
- Include context in logs (user ID, request ID, timestamp, etc.)
- Log all API requests and responses (with sensitive data redacted)
- Log errors with full stack traces and context
- Use correlation IDs to track requests across services
- Don't log sensitive information (passwords, tokens, credit cards)
- Implement log rotation and retention policies
- Use logging libraries (winston, pino, bunyan)

## Environment & Configuration
- Use .env files for environment-specific configuration
- Never commit .env files - use .env.example as template
- Use different configurations for development, staging, and production
- Validate required environment variables on application startup
- Use configuration management libraries (dotenv, config)
- Store secrets in environment variables or secret management services
- Use different database connections for different environments
- Configure CORS based on environment

## Performance Best Practices
- Implement caching where appropriate (Redis, in-memory cache)
- Use database query optimization (indexes, query analysis)
- Implement pagination for large datasets
- Use compression middleware (gzip, brotli)
- Implement request timeout handling
- Use connection pooling for database connections
- Avoid blocking the event loop with synchronous operations
- Use streaming for large file operations
- Implement rate limiting
- Use CDN for static assets
- Monitor and optimize slow queries
- Implement lazy loading where appropriate

## Testing Best Practices
- Write unit tests for business logic (services, utils)
- Write integration tests for API endpoints
- Write tests for error cases and edge cases
- Maintain test coverage above 80% for critical paths
- Use test-driven development (TDD) where appropriate
- Mock external dependencies (databases, APIs) in tests
- Use descriptive test names that explain what is being tested
- Keep tests independent and isolated
- Clean up test data after tests
- Use test fixtures and factories for test data
- Test both success and failure scenarios

## Code Quality
- Use ESLint for code linting
- Use Prettier for code formatting
- Implement pre-commit hooks for code quality checks
- Keep functions under 50 lines when possible
- Limit function parameters (max 3-4 parameters, use objects for more)
- Avoid deep nesting (max 3-4 levels)
- Use early returns to reduce nesting
- Remove unused code and dead code
- Keep dependencies up to date (security patches)
- Use TypeScript or JSDoc for type safety (if applicable)

## Documentation
- All features must be documented in project-docs
- Update documentation when adding new features
- Include parameter descriptions and return value explanations
- Document API endpoints (request/response formats, status codes, errors)
- Document environment variables and configuration
- Include code examples in documentation
- Document database schema and relationships
- Keep README.md updated with setup and usage instructions
- **API Documentation (Swagger/OpenAPI):**
  - All API endpoints must be documented with Swagger/OpenAPI JSDoc comments
  - Use `@swagger` annotations in route files to document endpoints
  - Include request/response schemas, parameters, and examples
  - Document authentication requirements using `security` tags
  - Add tags to group related endpoints
  - Swagger UI is available at `/api-docs` endpoint
  - Keep Swagger documentation in sync with code changes
  - Use reusable schemas defined in `src/config/swagger.ts` for common response types
  - Document all query parameters, path parameters, and request bodies
  - Include example values for better developer experience

## Git & Version Control
- Write clear, descriptive commit messages
- Use conventional commit format (feat:, fix:, docs:, etc.)
- Keep commits atomic (one logical change per commit)
- Don't commit sensitive data or large files
- Use .gitignore properly
- Create meaningful branch names
- Review code before merging

## Dependencies Management
- Keep dependencies up to date
- Use exact versions or lock files (package-lock.json, yarn.lock)
- Regularly audit dependencies for security vulnerabilities
- Remove unused dependencies
- Prefer well-maintained, popular libraries
- Document why specific dependencies are chosen

## Deployment & DevOps
- Use environment-specific configurations
- Implement health check endpoints (/health, /ready)
- Use process managers (PM2, systemd) in production
- Implement graceful shutdown
- Use containerization (Docker) for consistency
- Implement CI/CD pipelines
- Monitor application performance and errors
- Set up alerts for critical errors
- Implement backup and disaster recovery procedures
